WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.440 --> 00:00:04.300
Good afternoon. Thank you for joining us this afternoon for our session,

2
00:00:04.380 --> 00:00:07.900
From Risk Awareness to Informed Action Advancing Cancer

3
00:00:07.980 --> 00:00:11.240
Communication Across Prevention and Genomic

4
00:00:11.640 --> 00:00:14.180
Care. We have three speakers today.

5
00:00:15.580 --> 00:00:18.700
Dr. Jeffrey Niederdeppe from

6
00:00:18.940 --> 00:00:22.860
Cornell University in Ithaca, New York, Sarah

7
00:00:22.940 --> 00:00:26.380
Bauerly Bass from Philadelphia Temple University,

8
00:00:26.920 --> 00:00:30.600
and I'm Anita Kinney, and I'm at Rutgers Cancer Institute and Rutgers

9
00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:34.440
University. So this session is focused on strengthening cancer risk

10
00:00:34.460 --> 00:00:37.960
communication across prevention, screening, and precision

11
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.900
oncology. And the session highlights evidence-based communication

12
00:00:42.020 --> 00:00:45.480
strategies to help individuals, communities

13
00:00:45.820 --> 00:00:49.020
understand modifiable cancer risk factors, reduce

14
00:00:49.060 --> 00:00:52.900
disparities, and translate complex information

15
00:00:52.940 --> 00:00:56.370
into informed action. So our first speaker is Dr.

16
00:00:56.600 --> 00:00:57.560
Niederdeppe. Thank you.

17
00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:04.981
All right. Thanks, Anita.

18
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:07.860
Again, Jeff Niederdeppe, Cornell University.

19
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:12.460
And some of the work that I'm going to present today is

20
00:01:13.280 --> 00:01:16.700
supported by grants from NCI and NIH and reflect,

21
00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:17.760
of course,

22
00:01:18.820 --> 00:01:21.480
my own responsibility and not these agencies.

23
00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:26.010
So to start, I'm going to focus my comments today on the

24
00:01:26.100 --> 00:01:29.760
prevention and detection stages of the cancer

25
00:01:29.820 --> 00:01:33.230
control continuum. Not to say that some of the methods and

26
00:01:33.260 --> 00:01:37.020
approaches are not appropriate for questions about treatment

27
00:01:37.380 --> 00:01:41.360
and survivorship, but the focus of my work is predominantly prevention and

28
00:01:41.380 --> 00:01:41.810
detection.

29
00:01:43.580 --> 00:01:45.740
And I'm going to make three main points today.

30
00:01:45.780 --> 00:01:48.910
The first point I'm going to make, and I'll walk you through each of these, is that

31
00:01:48.960 --> 00:01:52.660
strategic and effective health communication often starts with the

32
00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:56.650
outcome you want to achieve and works backward, rather than starting with

33
00:01:56.680 --> 00:01:59.320
the message you want to convey and working forward.

34
00:02:00.620 --> 00:02:03.980
Second, the public communication environment, including

35
00:02:04.020 --> 00:02:07.860
increasingly, importantly, social media around cancer

36
00:02:07.940 --> 00:02:11.620
prevention behaviors, is competitive and complex, and we need to understand that

37
00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:15.240
competitiveness and complexity to message effectively.

38
00:02:16.260 --> 00:02:19.940
And third, that well-designed formative and evaluative messaging

39
00:02:20.040 --> 00:02:23.680
research can offer evidence-based strategies for effective

40
00:02:23.960 --> 00:02:25.190
cancer communication.

41
00:02:26.840 --> 00:02:29.900
So let me start with this first premise, that strategic behavior change

42
00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:32.760
starts with the outcome and works backward.

43
00:02:33.120 --> 00:02:35.720
When you work in cancer prevention or

44
00:02:36.760 --> 00:02:40.460
preventive medicine in general, we're around people all the time who are always

45
00:02:40.500 --> 00:02:43.940
thinking about cancer, and links between various risk

46
00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:47.920
factors and cancer. And I'm going to walk through a thought example

47
00:02:48.020 --> 00:02:51.410
here focused on messaging around the link between

48
00:02:51.460 --> 00:02:54.560
alcohol and cancer, a known risk factor.

49
00:02:55.360 --> 00:02:57.120
And if we start from the perspective of

50
00:02:59.380 --> 00:03:03.360
there's a link between alcohol and cancer and drinking less is good,

51
00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:07.300
we often may be tempted to say, "That's the message we need to convey if we want

52
00:03:07.680 --> 00:03:10.500
to promote people to drink less alcohol."

53
00:03:11.300 --> 00:03:14.920
But decades of theory and research on behavior

54
00:03:15.140 --> 00:03:19.040
change communication suggests that it's often productive to

55
00:03:19.120 --> 00:03:22.890
start with the outcome and work backward to understand the various

56
00:03:22.960 --> 00:03:25.660
kinds of beliefs that people hold about that behavior.

57
00:03:26.090 --> 00:03:29.920
Some of which may be links between, for instance, health risks and the

58
00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:33.940
behavior, but some of which may be about other things that are driving

59
00:03:34.020 --> 00:03:36.800
whether or not people choose to drink more or less.

60
00:03:36.870 --> 00:03:38.380
And so you can see some examples here.

61
00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:39.760
Certainly, some people

62
00:03:40.560 --> 00:03:44.300
are driven by beliefs about alcohol and cancer, but others may

63
00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:46.040
be motivated by other

64
00:03:46.960 --> 00:03:50.880
health risks or mental health or just feeling

65
00:03:50.900 --> 00:03:54.880
better, for instance. Beliefs about the social risks about alcohol may be

66
00:03:54.900 --> 00:03:58.200
driving whether or not people choose to drink less or more.

67
00:03:58.640 --> 00:04:00.080
Beliefs about the benefits of drinking.

68
00:04:00.120 --> 00:04:03.820
It's going to be a fun time or loosened inhibitions may be

69
00:04:03.840 --> 00:04:07.620
driving the behavior. Normative beliefs, what my friends do, what my colleagues do,

70
00:04:07.980 --> 00:04:11.720
and whether or not I even could, if I wanted to, drink

71
00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:12.900
less alcohol.

72
00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:18.250
Lots of work suggests that trying to understand which of these beliefs is

73
00:04:18.280 --> 00:04:22.260
driving the behavior and then developing messaging interventions to target

74
00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:26.230
those beliefs that are most important in shaping the behavior can lead

75
00:04:26.280 --> 00:04:28.320
to more effective messaging strategies.

76
00:04:28.360 --> 00:04:31.660
And that may include beliefs about, for instance,

77
00:04:32.120 --> 00:04:34.260
alcohol and cancer, but it may not.

78
00:04:36.180 --> 00:04:39.740
Also, if we start with the outcome and work backwards, we may open up different

79
00:04:39.800 --> 00:04:43.600
kinds of interventions or strategies that might prove to be effective.

80
00:04:43.640 --> 00:04:47.030
For instance, we know that reducing alcohol marketing or

81
00:04:47.060 --> 00:04:49.620
availability predicts less drinking.

82
00:04:49.660 --> 00:04:53.360
We know that increasing the cost, financial, of alcohol or the social

83
00:04:53.400 --> 00:04:56.860
cost of drinking, sanctions for drink driving, for

84
00:04:56.920 --> 00:05:00.760
instance, are associated with drinking less alcohol.

85
00:05:01.100 --> 00:05:04.920
And that may lead us to a different or similar set of

86
00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:08.780
messaging strategies that target whether or not people support or oppose these

87
00:05:08.840 --> 00:05:12.680
kinds of policies, which in turn create better, healthier

88
00:05:12.720 --> 00:05:14.920
environments for drinking less alcohol.

89
00:05:16.600 --> 00:05:20.060
All right. Second point I want to make here is that the public communication

90
00:05:20.080 --> 00:05:23.580
environment for cancer prevention behaviors, and lots of other behaviors for that

91
00:05:23.620 --> 00:05:27.220
matter, is competitive and complex, and that there is value to

92
00:05:27.260 --> 00:05:31.060
understanding it to identify opportunities for

93
00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:32.460
effective messaging.

94
00:05:34.020 --> 00:05:37.920
On the competitive side, I think it goes without saying, but I think illustrating

95
00:05:37.940 --> 00:05:41.610
the volume is quite illustrative, that messaging about,

96
00:05:41.780 --> 00:05:43.000
say, alcohol

97
00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:47.120
cancer and drinking

98
00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:51.080
less occurs in a competitive messaging environment where there are lots

99
00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:55.000
of companies who are messaging all about the ways that drinking more is

100
00:05:55.420 --> 00:05:58.380
a good thing. This is true for lots and lots of behaviors.

101
00:05:58.460 --> 00:06:02.370
Here I'm showing you data just based on its availability about impressions and

102
00:06:02.400 --> 00:06:05.210
expenditures by food and beverage companies.

103
00:06:05.840 --> 00:06:09.780
This data is from 2020 and 2021. And what we see here

104
00:06:09.820 --> 00:06:12.664
is thatFood and beverage companies spent,

105
00:06:12.984 --> 00:06:16.064
over a one-year period, over

106
00:06:16.074 --> 00:06:19.604
$2.7 billion marketing

107
00:06:20.264 --> 00:06:21.094
food and beverages,

108
00:06:22.404 --> 00:06:26.044
most likely not focusing on the health impacts of these.

109
00:06:26.104 --> 00:06:30.044
So I raise this just to say that any messaging we're doing is

110
00:06:30.084 --> 00:06:33.504
in competition with commercial marketing forces who

111
00:06:33.544 --> 00:06:36.884
dramatically outspend us, and we need to understand what kinds of messages are

112
00:06:36.904 --> 00:06:40.844
being conveyed about the products or behaviors that we are competing with

113
00:06:41.364 --> 00:06:44.604
in cancer risk or health communication.

114
00:06:46.644 --> 00:06:49.744
The second point I'll make here is that people are seeking and

115
00:06:49.864 --> 00:06:53.804
accessing health information from a wide range of sources, some of which

116
00:06:53.884 --> 00:06:56.164
may be credible and some of which may be not.

117
00:06:56.224 --> 00:07:00.024
These are data from a recent study, March 2025,

118
00:07:00.364 --> 00:07:03.744
on US women ages 21 to 65.

119
00:07:04.384 --> 00:07:07.883
The sources that they cited, seeking information about

120
00:07:07.984 --> 00:07:09.464
cervical cancer

121
00:07:10.404 --> 00:07:13.964
as a topic. And what we see here is that, yes,

122
00:07:14.304 --> 00:07:17.414
women in this age group are looking at health websites.

123
00:07:17.464 --> 00:07:21.254
About 73% say they look for information about cervical cancer from health

124
00:07:21.264 --> 00:07:25.064
websites, from search engines. But we also see some sort of maybe

125
00:07:25.164 --> 00:07:28.004
less obvious sources here. Social media,

126
00:07:28.264 --> 00:07:31.224
44% mention seeking

127
00:07:31.384 --> 00:07:33.864
information about cervical cancer.

128
00:07:34.224 --> 00:07:38.164
Generative AI, 40%. I bet you that number's higher today

129
00:07:38.244 --> 00:07:39.903
than it was even a year ago.

130
00:07:41.004 --> 00:07:44.964
And if you look at these numbers by women and men, for that matter, who

131
00:07:45.044 --> 00:07:48.484
are at the younger distribution of this age

132
00:07:48.944 --> 00:07:51.674
range, those numbers are actually quite a bit higher,

133
00:07:52.494 --> 00:07:55.664
social media, generative AI, for younger populations.

134
00:07:57.824 --> 00:08:01.264
So the centrality of social media platforms,

135
00:08:01.284 --> 00:08:05.084
particularly for young people, changes some things

136
00:08:05.644 --> 00:08:09.264
about health communication and what we need to know and understand, but it doesn't

137
00:08:09.304 --> 00:08:13.094
change everything. And I want to say a little bit about what I think it changes

138
00:08:13.644 --> 00:08:15.984
and a little bit about what I think it doesn't change.

139
00:08:17.064 --> 00:08:20.843
So what's different? Well, for one, social media platforms

140
00:08:21.084 --> 00:08:24.604
favor video over text, and they make it difficult

141
00:08:24.614 --> 00:08:28.244
to identify the original source of the message because they're often messages that

142
00:08:28.264 --> 00:08:32.095
are shared or reposted with editorial and commenting and

143
00:08:32.105 --> 00:08:35.264
things like that, which make it difficult to know where that message came from

144
00:08:35.485 --> 00:08:39.454
originally. Social media platforms privilege short messages

145
00:08:39.564 --> 00:08:43.413
over ones that have more nuance and complexity, and when we're dealing with cancer,

146
00:08:43.485 --> 00:08:47.224
we're often dealing with nuance and complexity.

147
00:08:47.254 --> 00:08:50.724
They rely on message retransmission, so we have to care not only

148
00:08:50.734 --> 00:08:54.324
about whether people see our messages, but whether or not people are sharing them

149
00:08:54.364 --> 00:08:57.864
and distributing them at scale, because the networked

150
00:08:58.044 --> 00:09:01.844
nature of our social media environments mean that a lot of the

151
00:09:01.884 --> 00:09:05.444
chances of whether or not people see a message depend on whether people are sharing

152
00:09:05.504 --> 00:09:09.344
those messages. But we also lose some control of the message when people

153
00:09:09.404 --> 00:09:11.624
share it, repost, comment, etc.

154
00:09:13.424 --> 00:09:16.904
They're inherently relational, meaning that we get information from people who are

155
00:09:16.944 --> 00:09:20.824
like us on social media platforms, and those messages tend to

156
00:09:20.864 --> 00:09:24.604
reinforce our existing beliefs and can encourage confirmation

157
00:09:24.664 --> 00:09:26.224
bias, things we think we already know.

158
00:09:27.624 --> 00:09:31.264
And finally, they may not reflect expert perspectives or

159
00:09:31.304 --> 00:09:35.064
messaging about cancer and health that we, in the cancer

160
00:09:35.144 --> 00:09:38.684
prevention space, would want or assume that

161
00:09:38.724 --> 00:09:39.944
people would

162
00:09:40.864 --> 00:09:42.103
need to be exposed to.

163
00:09:43.384 --> 00:09:46.744
Let me give you an example of what this looks like on social media messages

164
00:09:47.464 --> 00:09:51.124
about cancer. Here, we have a study led by my colleague Andy King

165
00:09:52.004 --> 00:09:55.084
of messages about five different

166
00:09:55.564 --> 00:09:59.524
cancers. You see there in this chart, breast

167
00:09:59.564 --> 00:10:03.504
cancer, colon cancer, esophageal cancer, liver cancer, and oral cancer.

168
00:10:03.624 --> 00:10:05.424
All cancers that are associated

169
00:10:06.264 --> 00:10:06.484
with

170
00:10:07.344 --> 00:10:11.264
reduced risk of drinking, as predicts onset of these cancers.

171
00:10:12.084 --> 00:10:16.044
And this is a sample of messages that used these hashtags or hashtags

172
00:10:16.084 --> 00:10:20.014
that are similar to these on Twitter between 2019 and

173
00:10:20.104 --> 00:10:24.084
2021. The point I want to make here, if you look at the far right

174
00:10:24.184 --> 00:10:27.924
column, is that messages that talk about these cancers on social media

175
00:10:28.664 --> 00:10:32.424
almost never mention alcohol. Even for liver cancer,

176
00:10:32.524 --> 00:10:36.384
it's less than 2% of messages

177
00:10:36.484 --> 00:10:40.124
mention alcohol. And in some cases, when alcohol is mentioned, it's not

178
00:10:40.964 --> 00:10:44.484
a risk message, but it's instead a sort of alcohol sponsor or a

179
00:10:44.764 --> 00:10:48.504
pro alcohol message. So this is to say messages

180
00:10:48.564 --> 00:10:52.304
about these cancers on social media are not talking

181
00:10:52.364 --> 00:10:54.904
about the role of cancer, for instance.

182
00:10:56.844 --> 00:10:59.564
We also are looking at messages on TikTok.

183
00:10:59.784 --> 00:11:03.324
This is data from an ongoing study where we're looking at

184
00:11:03.984 --> 00:11:07.704
specifically hashtags that are focused on either

185
00:11:07.764 --> 00:11:10.904
alcohol reduction, drinking less, or alcohol

186
00:11:11.044 --> 00:11:13.874
cessation, quitting drinking entirely.

187
00:11:14.524 --> 00:11:18.114
And these are messages that have appeared on TikTok between 2021 and

188
00:11:18.304 --> 00:11:21.624
2025. And I'll point out two things from these data.

189
00:11:21.764 --> 00:11:23.824
One is that a lot of the

190
00:11:24.804 --> 00:11:28.664
messages on TikTok that are tagged with hashtags that say things like "drink

191
00:11:28.744 --> 00:11:32.584
less" or "drink responsibly" actually aren't about alcohol at all.

192
00:11:32.824 --> 00:11:36.304
The vast majority of these are not directly relevant to this topic.

193
00:11:37.244 --> 00:11:41.064
But even when they are, they almost never mention cancer

194
00:11:41.144 --> 00:11:44.964
as a reason to drink less or as a reason to not

195
00:11:45.024 --> 00:11:46.104
drink at all, to

196
00:11:47.104 --> 00:11:51.074
be cessation from alcohol. And so I raise this to say, for those

197
00:11:51.104 --> 00:11:55.024
of us who are spending our lives thinking about different carcinogens and different

198
00:11:55.304 --> 00:11:58.684
risk factors for cancer and increasingly

199
00:11:58.964 --> 00:12:00.904
focusing, I think, on the role of alcohol,

200
00:12:02.124 --> 00:12:05.604
this is not so much happening in the social media platforms in which people are

201
00:12:05.644 --> 00:12:07.704
getting lots of their information.

202
00:12:08.224 --> 00:12:10.504
So this is both an opportunity and a challenge, right?

203
00:12:10.544 --> 00:12:14.514
We have a messaging environment that's not amplifying messages

204
00:12:14.584 --> 00:12:18.504
about alcohol, but potentially a chance to do so through our own

205
00:12:18.544 --> 00:12:22.274
interventions.Now, what's the same about

206
00:12:22.314 --> 00:12:22.914
social media?

207
00:12:23.834 --> 00:12:25.214
I said before that some things are different.

208
00:12:25.274 --> 00:12:28.954
I talked about what's different, but lots of principles are exactly the same.

209
00:12:29.314 --> 00:12:33.254
Public health communication has always had to meet audiences where

210
00:12:33.334 --> 00:12:34.754
they are, whether on TV,

211
00:12:35.614 --> 00:12:39.564
online, or on social media. That has not changed, despite that

212
00:12:39.594 --> 00:12:42.874
people's media habits have changed, and we need to follow them.

213
00:12:43.634 --> 00:12:47.614
We've always had to compete with well-funded industry forces who

214
00:12:47.694 --> 00:12:51.554
spend more money than we'll ever have in prevention, and public

215
00:12:51.594 --> 00:12:55.494
health, and cancer prevention. We've always needed to identify

216
00:12:55.554 --> 00:12:58.184
credible sources to communicate about public health.

217
00:12:58.554 --> 00:13:02.104
Now, the nature of those sources, who is found credible, may

218
00:13:02.154 --> 00:13:06.124
evolve over time. We're at a moment when certainly public health is not

219
00:13:06.154 --> 00:13:09.734
experiencing high levels of public trust, but that doesn't change the fact that we

220
00:13:09.754 --> 00:13:13.174
need to identify sources that are seen as credible by our audiences.

221
00:13:14.514 --> 00:13:18.034
We need to learn and create opportunities for exchange and

222
00:13:18.074 --> 00:13:21.374
feedback on the messages that we're developing from

223
00:13:21.384 --> 00:13:25.174
audiences who are experiencing the world, likely in different ways

224
00:13:25.614 --> 00:13:26.674
than we are from our

225
00:13:27.574 --> 00:13:31.094
roles as health communicators or in the

226
00:13:31.134 --> 00:13:32.194
health system.

227
00:13:33.334 --> 00:13:36.994
And finally, we've always needed to find ways to invite people to engage

228
00:13:37.094 --> 00:13:40.474
with more complex, longer form messages for

229
00:13:41.034 --> 00:13:44.914
complicated and uncertain science related to cancer

230
00:13:44.974 --> 00:13:45.454
prevention.

231
00:13:47.374 --> 00:13:50.894
All right. I'm going to spend the last couple of minutes talking about making a

232
00:13:50.954 --> 00:13:54.134
case that well-designed, formative, and evaluative messaging

233
00:13:54.194 --> 00:13:58.094
research can offer evidence-based guidance

234
00:13:58.114 --> 00:14:01.874
for effective cancer communication, although it's not a panacea

235
00:14:02.254 --> 00:14:02.594
either.

236
00:14:04.134 --> 00:14:08.064
The way that we tend to approach studying and developing messages

237
00:14:08.174 --> 00:14:11.314
for cancer prevention begins with what I've already talked about, trying to

238
00:14:11.354 --> 00:14:15.174
understand what messages are out there in our health websites, in news

239
00:14:15.234 --> 00:14:19.134
articles, and in social media to understand what people are seeing in

240
00:14:19.174 --> 00:14:20.114
their daily lives.

241
00:14:21.054 --> 00:14:24.834
And then to learn how people are responding to these messages by sampling

242
00:14:24.874 --> 00:14:28.834
them, and then doing various methods to crowdsource

243
00:14:28.894 --> 00:14:32.754
or to identify messages that seem to resonate among diverse

244
00:14:32.954 --> 00:14:36.694
audiences, including populations who experience disparities.

245
00:14:37.414 --> 00:14:40.974
And then take that information and formally test the impact of these messages

246
00:14:41.394 --> 00:14:45.194
using tried and true methods like randomized control trials that I'm sure

247
00:14:45.374 --> 00:14:49.304
are quite familiar to folks in this room to provide strong,

248
00:14:49.474 --> 00:14:51.483
causal, evidence-based guidance.

249
00:14:52.434 --> 00:14:55.924
Let me walk you through an example of what we've done recently in this space.

250
00:14:57.014 --> 00:15:00.294
I'm switching now to a focus on a project that is promoting

251
00:15:00.694 --> 00:15:02.574
colorectal cancer screening.

252
00:15:03.474 --> 00:15:07.314
And in this study, we sampled over 2,000

253
00:15:07.434 --> 00:15:09.614
Black and White Americans of

254
00:15:09.934 --> 00:15:13.894
screening-recommended eligible age, 45 to 74,

255
00:15:14.254 --> 00:15:17.634
who had no prior colorectal cancer diagnosis.

256
00:15:18.254 --> 00:15:21.474
And we recruited them from a panel in '23 and

257
00:15:21.514 --> 00:15:24.804
'24 that seeks to use probability

258
00:15:24.854 --> 00:15:28.714
sampling to develop what are reasonable approximations for a

259
00:15:28.734 --> 00:15:30.394
nationally representative sample.

260
00:15:31.334 --> 00:15:34.834
And in this study, what we did is we gave them what's called a wiki

261
00:15:34.994 --> 00:15:38.794
survey, which is functionally a choice experiment where

262
00:15:38.834 --> 00:15:42.394
you ask people to choose between two messages, which they

263
00:15:42.454 --> 00:15:46.214
find more or less persuasive. And in this case, we gave them an opportunity to

264
00:15:46.254 --> 00:15:49.614
nominate their own user-generated messages for

265
00:15:49.634 --> 00:15:53.184
potential inclusion. And so we sampled about

266
00:15:53.334 --> 00:15:57.184
63 messages from the public communication environment, from social media and

267
00:15:57.234 --> 00:16:00.514
health websites, and we added 30 or so more

268
00:16:00.594 --> 00:16:02.924
user-generated messages for testing.

269
00:16:03.874 --> 00:16:07.543
So what does this look like? Respondents were shown 20 pairs of messages,

270
00:16:07.954 --> 00:16:11.654
and each of them were asked to read each message, message

271
00:16:11.834 --> 00:16:15.654
A and message B, and we asked them, "Which of these messages

272
00:16:15.834 --> 00:16:19.714
is more likely to make you, A, want to get screened for

273
00:16:19.774 --> 00:16:23.414
colorectal cancer? Or B, given how messages

274
00:16:23.814 --> 00:16:27.374
transmit in social media, which would you be more likely to

275
00:16:27.414 --> 00:16:31.364
share with your family and friends?" And then if they wanted to, they had the

276
00:16:31.434 --> 00:16:35.004
option to add an additional message, which we read and

277
00:16:35.114 --> 00:16:38.634
screened and added several into our choice set.

278
00:16:39.714 --> 00:16:39.954
And so

279
00:16:40.934 --> 00:16:44.914
after making sense of these data, what we can do is rank these messages in terms

280
00:16:44.994 --> 00:16:47.954
of ones that were perceived as more or less effective.

281
00:16:48.254 --> 00:16:52.194
And in this case, what we did is we stratified our sample by race because

282
00:16:52.254 --> 00:16:55.954
it turned out that information on which

283
00:16:56.014 --> 00:16:59.894
messages were perceived as highly effective and shareable differed pretty

284
00:16:59.914 --> 00:17:02.234
substantially between White and Black Americans.

285
00:17:02.754 --> 00:17:06.274
So what I'm showing you here is our top five rated messages among White Americans.

286
00:17:06.315 --> 00:17:10.075
I'm not going to ask you to read these messages, but I'll point out just a couple

287
00:17:10.114 --> 00:17:14.024
of things. One, messages that were rated highly among White respondents were

288
00:17:14.075 --> 00:17:17.974
generally also rated highly among Black respondents.

289
00:17:18.014 --> 00:17:21.374
Maybe not quite the first, second, or third, but still top

290
00:17:22.134 --> 00:17:22.954
quartile or so.

291
00:17:24.075 --> 00:17:27.964
And the one in italics was a user-generated message,

292
00:17:28.055 --> 00:17:31.894
suggesting there's pretty substantial value to understanding and

293
00:17:32.034 --> 00:17:35.734
learning from a crowdsourcing and user-generated way.

294
00:17:37.434 --> 00:17:40.964
If we turn to messages that were perceived as most effective by Black respondents,

295
00:17:41.014 --> 00:17:44.874
we see a very different pattern. The first, second,

296
00:17:44.934 --> 00:17:48.254
and fourth rated message among African Americans or Black respondents

297
00:17:48.754 --> 00:17:52.014
were rated as some of the lowest perceived effective

298
00:17:52.394 --> 00:17:56.194
among White respondents. And it's pretty clear, I think, to see

299
00:17:56.254 --> 00:18:00.174
what is driving that. Messages that were rated as highly effective

300
00:18:00.234 --> 00:18:03.974
among Black respondents tended to specify that we were speaking to

301
00:18:04.034 --> 00:18:07.874
African Americans, Black men, Black women, Black people, African

302
00:18:07.914 --> 00:18:11.814
Americans in these messages. And White respondents very

303
00:18:11.854 --> 00:18:15.074
much rated these in their own terms as less

304
00:18:15.434 --> 00:18:19.254
potentially effective. There were a couple messages, again, number three and

305
00:18:19.374 --> 00:18:23.294
five among Black Americans, that were also rated as highly

306
00:18:23.314 --> 00:18:27.194
effective among White Americans, but these did not specify anything about the

307
00:18:27.234 --> 00:18:30.124
racial identity of the potential audience or

308
00:18:30.614 --> 00:18:34.510
risk of colorectal cancer.So then

309
00:18:34.530 --> 00:18:38.250
we took this information, and we wanted to sort of validate whether or not

310
00:18:38.310 --> 00:18:42.110
these perceived message effectiveness ratings would translate

311
00:18:42.150 --> 00:18:45.730
into changing actual intentions to adhere to screening guidelines.

312
00:18:45.930 --> 00:18:49.790
So we took another sample. We're using the same panel, NORC

313
00:18:49.830 --> 00:18:53.810
AmeriSpeak, of about 1,000 white respondents and about 1,000 Black respondents.

314
00:18:54.630 --> 00:18:55.870
But these were different people,

315
00:18:56.670 --> 00:19:00.570
so not the same respondents. And we randomized them into five treatment

316
00:19:00.690 --> 00:19:04.650
arms. And folks who received a messaging condition saw

317
00:19:04.730 --> 00:19:07.310
six different social media posts.

318
00:19:08.470 --> 00:19:12.440
And then we compare intentions to adhere to screening recommendations

319
00:19:12.450 --> 00:19:16.190
and message sharing intentions by message condition and racial group.

320
00:19:17.150 --> 00:19:18.690
This is what the randomization looks like.

321
00:19:19.110 --> 00:19:22.450
We had a control group who saw nothing. They just answered the questions.

322
00:19:22.710 --> 00:19:26.090
They're our comparison group. And then we have four messaging conditions.

323
00:19:26.110 --> 00:19:30.100
The first saw messages that were about average, median ranked by

324
00:19:30.130 --> 00:19:33.610
everyone. A second group saw messages that were preferred by white

325
00:19:33.650 --> 00:19:37.310
Americans in our previous study. The third group saw messages that were

326
00:19:37.330 --> 00:19:39.570
preferred by Black Americans in our previous study.

327
00:19:40.070 --> 00:19:43.970
And the fourth sort of final treatment group had messages

328
00:19:44.030 --> 00:19:47.990
that were, overall, by both white and Black Americans, perceived as being

329
00:19:48.050 --> 00:19:50.790
highly effective. Were they actually effective?

330
00:19:51.830 --> 00:19:54.430
Just to give you a sense, these are what these messages looked like.

331
00:19:54.490 --> 00:19:57.850
They were like a social media post, but we didn't make them platform

332
00:19:58.050 --> 00:20:01.750
specific and took the text from our previous arm of the

333
00:20:01.790 --> 00:20:02.070
study.

334
00:20:03.950 --> 00:20:07.670
So turning to results, I'm showing you results here for Black adults

335
00:20:07.770 --> 00:20:11.290
ages 45 to 74, and we see here that first,

336
00:20:11.930 --> 00:20:15.910
every single messaging condition produced higher levels of intentions to adhere to

337
00:20:15.950 --> 00:20:19.690
screening recommendations than people who got no message at all.

338
00:20:20.230 --> 00:20:23.850
But we see sort of the highest mean levels happening for those

339
00:20:24.150 --> 00:20:27.850
who saw either Black preferred messages or overall preferred

340
00:20:27.910 --> 00:20:30.990
messages. But the median scored messages fared pretty well.

341
00:20:31.110 --> 00:20:34.250
The white preferred messages scored a little less favorably.

342
00:20:35.410 --> 00:20:39.190
But for white respondents, none of the messages moved the needle on increasing

343
00:20:39.490 --> 00:20:43.270
adherence to screening recommendations, regardless of whether they were targeted,

344
00:20:43.609 --> 00:20:44.889
preferred, or not.

345
00:20:46.110 --> 00:20:49.990
Finally, if we look at intentions to share, we see a pretty clear pattern

346
00:20:50.050 --> 00:20:53.990
here, where Black preferred messages were more likely to

347
00:20:54.050 --> 00:20:57.850
be intended to be shared by Black respondents, and white preferred

348
00:20:57.890 --> 00:21:00.850
messages were less likely to be shared by Black respondents.

349
00:21:01.870 --> 00:21:05.030
And the flip side was true for white respondents who were more likely to want to

350
00:21:05.070 --> 00:21:08.630
share messages that, in the previous study, white respondents had preferred.

351
00:21:10.050 --> 00:21:12.940
So I will close by saying what I said at the beginning,

352
00:21:13.910 --> 00:21:17.700
that decades of behavior change theory, research, and evidence

353
00:21:17.770 --> 00:21:21.739
suggests that effective health communication starts with the outcome you want and

354
00:21:21.770 --> 00:21:25.330
works backwards, rather than starting with a message about risk

355
00:21:25.630 --> 00:21:26.890
and moving from there.

356
00:21:28.270 --> 00:21:30.710
That the public communication environment is complex,

357
00:21:31.670 --> 00:21:32.230
and

358
00:21:33.290 --> 00:21:36.570
understanding it reveals both gaps in messaging but also

359
00:21:36.650 --> 00:21:39.490
opportunities for effective communication.

360
00:21:40.270 --> 00:21:44.090
And that well-designed formative research can offer

361
00:21:44.110 --> 00:21:47.910
evidence-based guidance. But this is not a panacea by any stretch.

362
00:21:47.950 --> 00:21:50.090
It's not a guarantee we're going to see effectiveness.

363
00:21:50.270 --> 00:21:50.590
And

364
00:21:51.450 --> 00:21:55.070
I think Sarah will speak a lot about this idea that segmenting

365
00:21:55.080 --> 00:21:58.930
audiences by meaningful differences in message preferences and message

366
00:21:59.570 --> 00:22:03.490
risk is tremendously important and underscored by our

367
00:22:03.500 --> 00:22:04.190
data here.

368
00:22:05.130 --> 00:22:07.410
I will stop there and open it up for questions. Thank you.

369
00:22:12.210 --> 00:22:15.890
I just ask that people come to the mic because we have people streaming, and so

370
00:22:15.930 --> 00:22:17.430
they need to be able to hear you. Thank you.

371
00:22:20.190 --> 00:22:20.470
Go ahead.

372
00:22:20.670 --> 00:22:24.070
Thanks a lot. Suzanne de la Loge from France. I have two questions.

373
00:22:24.090 --> 00:22:24.970
The first is,

374
00:22:26.250 --> 00:22:30.170
well, how much are participative messages, meaning

375
00:22:30.910 --> 00:22:33.130
messages that have been concepted with

376
00:22:34.610 --> 00:22:36.510
real people, how much do they

377
00:22:37.370 --> 00:22:41.310
impact the results that you observe versus non-participative messages?

378
00:22:42.710 --> 00:22:46.600
So the messages that we were testing, they were a combination of messages

379
00:22:46.630 --> 00:22:49.870
that were user-generated and generated from laypeople, but

380
00:22:49.950 --> 00:22:53.560
also by accounts like the American Cancer Society and

381
00:22:54.670 --> 00:22:56.550
NIH and other sorts of cancer centers.

382
00:22:56.630 --> 00:23:00.130
So it was a combination of both expert, I guess I would say, designed

383
00:23:00.190 --> 00:23:02.690
messages and lay-designed messages.

384
00:23:03.190 --> 00:23:07.150
But in both cases, some of the user-designed messages rose to

385
00:23:07.170 --> 00:23:10.930
the top. They were some of the messages that were perceived as at

386
00:23:10.990 --> 00:23:14.970
least in the upper tier of message effectiveness.

387
00:23:15.030 --> 00:23:18.930
So I think it speaks to the fact that there's value in both.

388
00:23:19.230 --> 00:23:22.710
Obviously, those messages from expert sources I think are

389
00:23:22.730 --> 00:23:23.950
designed with

390
00:23:25.170 --> 00:23:26.790
some research and evidence behind them.

391
00:23:26.850 --> 00:23:30.630
But spending some time understanding what emerges naturally, I think

392
00:23:30.710 --> 00:23:34.500
also can help us understand how people are thinking about these

393
00:23:34.550 --> 00:23:34.810
issues.

394
00:23:35.230 --> 00:23:39.150
Well, and a secondary question to that would be that some of the messages are quite

395
00:23:39.310 --> 00:23:41.550
biased in terms of science, et cetera.

396
00:23:42.430 --> 00:23:46.410
They're very appealing. And in terms of ethics, I

397
00:23:46.450 --> 00:23:49.930
don't know, in my country, some of these messages might be forbidden.

398
00:23:50.770 --> 00:23:54.730
Not considered ethic because imbalanced, et cetera.

399
00:23:54.830 --> 00:23:58.050
So it's always a balance between what we should do,

400
00:23:59.890 --> 00:24:02.750
what is used outside of medicine and science.

401
00:24:03.590 --> 00:24:05.730
So I don't know how to answer that question, but...

402
00:24:05.770 --> 00:24:07.230
Yeah, I'll say two things. One, we

403
00:24:08.790 --> 00:24:12.150
sort of curated them a bit. We did not include any messages that included anything

404
00:24:12.170 --> 00:24:15.530
that was factually wrong. That was incorrect.

405
00:24:15.590 --> 00:24:18.870
So some were saying, like, "Oh, you need to get screened when you're 18."

406
00:24:20.170 --> 00:24:24.050
But there are cases where colonoscopies are helpful for people who are 18 if a

407
00:24:24.070 --> 00:24:26.070
doctor is recommending that based on-...

408
00:24:26.110 --> 00:24:29.230
symptoms or family history, but that's not the screening recommendation, and so we

409
00:24:29.270 --> 00:24:33.149
didn't do anything that was outside of evidence-based communication.

410
00:24:33.170 --> 00:24:37.130
But that is to say, some of the messages focus on things that are not an

411
00:24:37.170 --> 00:24:41.030
emphasis of clinical research, talking about

412
00:24:41.070 --> 00:24:44.770
how the process of getting a colonoscopy, for

413
00:24:44.830 --> 00:24:48.740
instance. Or, "The prep isn't as bad as you think,

414
00:24:48.810 --> 00:24:52.690
and the trade-off is worth it." So these are messages, I think,

415
00:24:52.730 --> 00:24:53.250
that aren't

416
00:24:54.770 --> 00:24:58.110
reporting on scientific evidence per se, but are about lived

417
00:24:58.150 --> 00:25:01.310
experience of engaging in the behaviors. But I agree with you.

418
00:25:01.410 --> 00:25:05.250
It's very important, obviously, not to be spreading factually

419
00:25:05.290 --> 00:25:07.630
false information, and you need

420
00:25:09.890 --> 00:25:13.889
some mechanism of screening and curation in order to do that.

421
00:25:14.770 --> 00:25:18.270
Okay, and a small last question. Well, it's not small, but

422
00:25:18.650 --> 00:25:20.850
it's always so striking to me that

423
00:25:21.730 --> 00:25:25.030
religious messages on alcohol, especially, are so efficient.

424
00:25:25.170 --> 00:25:28.150
It's both religious and community, but

425
00:25:29.889 --> 00:25:33.810
well, it's incredible to me almost every day that it's so efficient

426
00:25:33.890 --> 00:25:37.270
as compared to whatever we can do to prevent people from

427
00:25:37.550 --> 00:25:39.270
drinking, for instance. And

428
00:25:40.210 --> 00:25:44.150
I'm just wondering how much we should work on that and see what

429
00:25:45.210 --> 00:25:49.060
that kind of mechanism, could it be used outside of religious and

430
00:25:49.150 --> 00:25:50.590
community context? And

431
00:25:51.410 --> 00:25:53.030
of course, it's very different, but

432
00:25:54.070 --> 00:25:55.810
well, the solution could be there.

433
00:25:56.770 --> 00:25:57.430
Yeah. I think

434
00:25:58.550 --> 00:26:02.270
the interaction between the source and the content of the message is really, really

435
00:26:02.330 --> 00:26:06.200
important, right? I'm not sure that I want my primary care provider

436
00:26:06.770 --> 00:26:10.720
bringing religious themes into the messaging about my

437
00:26:10.750 --> 00:26:14.290
risk or my behaviors. So there are some kinds of messages that an

438
00:26:14.310 --> 00:26:17.500
oncologist or a doctor is going to be well-positioned to do, but there are other

439
00:26:17.530 --> 00:26:20.820
kinds of messages, and I think from a prevention and

440
00:26:20.890 --> 00:26:24.830
campaign development perspective, identifying partners who

441
00:26:24.870 --> 00:26:28.850
share the same goal and yet have different sources

442
00:26:29.050 --> 00:26:32.450
of trust or credibility with audiences.

443
00:26:32.530 --> 00:26:36.450
So certainly, religious leaders or even just other everyday

444
00:26:36.530 --> 00:26:37.110
people who

445
00:26:37.970 --> 00:26:38.750
are choosing

446
00:26:40.130 --> 00:26:44.050
to drink less or not drink at all, in these cases, due to religious reasons,

447
00:26:44.110 --> 00:26:46.410
that's going to resonate with some people.

448
00:26:46.830 --> 00:26:50.690
And some people are going to be more credible messengers of that kind of

449
00:26:50.710 --> 00:26:51.450
message than others.

450
00:26:51.630 --> 00:26:52.250
Thank you very much.

451
00:26:52.450 --> 00:26:53.049
Thank you.

452
00:26:54.710 --> 00:26:56.470
Hi. A little more general question.

453
00:26:56.530 --> 00:27:00.110
I was just wondering if any work has been done or if there's any information

454
00:27:00.150 --> 00:27:01.870
available that addresses

455
00:27:03.110 --> 00:27:06.690
a distrust that the public tends to have sometimes of healthcare

456
00:27:06.810 --> 00:27:09.390
scientists or even their own doctors.

457
00:27:09.890 --> 00:27:13.790
I was wondering if there's anything about how

458
00:27:13.850 --> 00:27:17.750
that impacts the ability to get those messages across that we're trying to

459
00:27:17.770 --> 00:27:18.370
communicate,

460
00:27:19.170 --> 00:27:21.350
or any strategies that can address that.

461
00:27:21.810 --> 00:27:22.910
Yeah. Great question.

462
00:27:23.990 --> 00:27:27.690
So yes, there's lots of work that has been looking at declining

463
00:27:27.770 --> 00:27:31.570
trust in institutions, declining trust, certainly, in

464
00:27:31.670 --> 00:27:35.510
our federal messengers about

465
00:27:35.590 --> 00:27:39.130
health. But your

466
00:27:39.210 --> 00:27:43.110
own primary doctor has held pretty steady over

467
00:27:43.150 --> 00:27:47.070
that time, generally speaking. There's also obvious social patterns

468
00:27:47.110 --> 00:27:50.670
and historical reasons why different populations distrust medical

469
00:27:50.790 --> 00:27:51.910
systems and authorities.

470
00:27:52.810 --> 00:27:56.330
Some of them well-earned due to racism and

471
00:27:56.370 --> 00:27:59.090
discrimination in health systems, for instance.

472
00:27:59.690 --> 00:28:03.450
And so, I think it goes back to this idea of

473
00:28:03.510 --> 00:28:07.310
needing to identify credible sources who may or may not be

474
00:28:07.630 --> 00:28:11.470
institutional actors, who may or may not be

475
00:28:11.550 --> 00:28:15.150
people wearing a white coat in a

476
00:28:15.190 --> 00:28:17.890
laboratory or in a clinical setting.

477
00:28:18.220 --> 00:28:21.430
That's going to differ depending on which audience you're engaging with.

478
00:28:21.530 --> 00:28:25.380
So there's not one sort of size-fits-all kind of

479
00:28:25.410 --> 00:28:27.350
credible source for all sorts of information.

480
00:28:27.510 --> 00:28:28.030
That said,

481
00:28:28.950 --> 00:28:32.830
primary care physicians still, I think, have quite a bit of

482
00:28:32.890 --> 00:28:34.090
trust for those

483
00:28:34.990 --> 00:28:38.910
people who have access to primary care and have a doctor

484
00:28:38.930 --> 00:28:40.850
that they've built a relationship with over time.

485
00:28:40.890 --> 00:28:44.459
So those remain very important relationships that

486
00:28:44.490 --> 00:28:47.170
are constrained by lots and lots of factors

487
00:28:47.449 --> 00:28:50.670
as to how long those interactions can be,

488
00:28:50.710 --> 00:28:53.630
frequency of engagement with doctors.

489
00:28:53.670 --> 00:28:57.630
So I think without a doubt, there's a need to think more broadly

490
00:28:57.730 --> 00:29:00.790
than simply within health systems about messaging.

491
00:29:01.370 --> 00:29:05.050
But who are those resonant audiences, I think, is a moving

492
00:29:05.110 --> 00:29:09.030
target over time, and that's the role of formative research, is

493
00:29:09.070 --> 00:29:12.750
to identify who those groups are that resonate at the community level for

494
00:29:12.770 --> 00:29:13.849
particular populations.

495
00:29:14.230 --> 00:29:14.770
Thank you.

496
00:29:15.150 --> 00:29:15.450
Thank you.

497
00:29:16.010 --> 00:29:19.570
Yeah. Quick question about the study in terms of the messaging.

498
00:29:19.610 --> 00:29:23.570
